In the Mon script, consonants belong to one of two registers: clear and breathy, each of which has different inherent vowels and pronunciations for the same set of diacritics. For instance, {{my|<U+1000>}}, which belongs to the clear register, is pronounced {{IPA|/ka<U+02C0>/}}, while {{my|<U+1002>}} is pronounced {{IPA|/<U+0261><U+025B><U+0300><U+02C0>/}}, to accommodate the vowel complexity of the Mon phonology.<ref>{{cite book |title=Concise encyclopedia of languages of the world |chapter=Mon |year=2009 |publisher=Elsevier |location= |isbn=9780080877747 |pages=719<U+2013>20 |accessdate=2010-09-29}}</ref> The addition of diacritics makes this obvious. Whereas in Burmese, spellings with the same diacritics are rhyming, in Mon, this depends on the consonant's inherent register. A few examples are listed below:
* {{my|<U+1000>}} + {{my|<U+102E>}} <U+2192> {{my|<U+1000><U+102E>}}, pronounced {{IPA|/k<U+0254>e/}}
* {{my|<U+1002>}} + {{my|<U+102E>}} <U+2192> {{my|<U+1002><U+102E>}}, pronounced {{IPA|/k<U+00EC>/}}
* {{my|<U+1000>}} + {{my|<U+1030>}} <U+2192> {{my|<U+1000><U+1030>}}, pronounced {{IPA|/kao/}}
* {{my|<U+1002>}} + {{my|<U+1030>}} <U+2192> {{my|<U+1002><U+1030>}}, pronounced {{IPA|/k<U+00F9>/}}
   
Mon uses the same diacritics and diacritic combinations as in Burmese to represent vowels, with the addition of a few diacritics unique to the Mon script, including {{my|<U+1034>}} ({{IPA|/<U+025B><U+0300>a/}}), and {{my|<U+1033>}} ({{IPA|/i/}}), since the diacritic {{my|<U+102D>}} represents {{IPA|/<U+00EC><U+02C0>/}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/31170845/Mon-Vowels-Characters |title=Mon Vowels Characters |author=Dho-ong Jhaan |date=2010-05-10 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=12 September 2010}}</ref> Also, {{my|<U+1028>}} ({{IPA|/e/}}) is used instead of {{my|<U+1027>}}, as in Burmese. 

The Mon language has 8 medials, as follows: {{my|<U+1039><U+105A>}} ({{IPA|/-<U+014B>-/}}), {{my|<U+105E>}} ({{IPA|/-n-/}}), {{my|<U+105F>}} ({{IPA|/-m-/}}), {{my|<U+103B>}} ({{IPA|/-j-/}}), {{my|<U+103C>}} ({{IPA|/-r-/}}), {{my|<U+1060>}} ({{IPA|/-l-/}}), {{my|<U+103D>}} ({{IPA|/-w-/}}), and {{my|<U+103E>}} ({{IPA|/-hn-/}}). Consonantal finals are indicated with a [[virama]] ({{my|<U+103A>}}), as in Burmese. Furthermore, consonant stacking is possible in Mon spellings, particularly for [[Pali]] and [[Sanskrit]]-derived vocabulary.

